But to go to the question about better, people better, there's zero evidence that smart people

50:36.840 --> 50:46.680
are better with respect to important aspects of life, like honesty, even likability.

50:47.880 --> 50:53.320
I'm sure you know many very intelligent people who are not terribly likable or terribly kind

50:53.320 --> 50:59.720
or terribly honest. Is there something to be said? So one of the things I've recently reread

50:59.720 --> 51:07.880
for the second time, I guess that's what the word reread means, the rise and fall of the third

51:07.880 --> 51:16.440
Reich, which is I think the best telling of the rise and fall of Hitler. And one of the interesting

51:16.440 --> 51:32.280
things about the people that, how should I say it, justified or maybe propped up the ideas

51:32.280 --> 51:39.160
that Hitler put forward is the fact that they were extremely intelligent. They were in the

51:39.160 --> 51:49.400
intellectual class. It was obvious that they thought very deeply and rationally about the world.

51:49.400 --> 51:55.960
So what I would like to say is one of the things that shows to me is some of the worst atrocities

51:55.960 --> 52:03.640
in the history of humanity have been committed by very intelligent people. So that means that

52:03.720 --> 52:12.680
intelligence doesn't make you a good person. I wonder if there's a g-factor for intelligence.

52:12.680 --> 52:19.640
I wonder if there's a g-factor for goodness. The Nietzschean good and evil, of course that's

52:19.640 --> 52:24.200
probably harder to measure because it's such a subjective thing, what it means to be good.

52:25.240 --> 52:30.280
And even the idea of evil is a deeply uncomfortable thing because how do we know?

52:31.160 --> 52:37.000
But it's independent, whatever it is, it's independent of intelligence. So I agree with you

52:37.000 --> 52:45.800
about that. But let me say this, I have also asserted my belief that more intelligence is

52:45.800 --> 52:55.320
better than less. It doesn't mean more intelligent people are better people, but all things being

52:55.320 --> 53:01.160
equal, would you like to be smarter or less smart? So if I had a pill, I have two pills,

53:01.160 --> 53:05.480
I said, this one will make you smarter, this one will make you dumber. Which one would you like?

53:06.360 --> 53:10.760
Are there any circumstances under which you would choose to be dumber? Well, let me ask you this.

53:11.480 --> 53:17.800
That's a very nuanced and interesting question. You know, there's been books written about this,

53:17.800 --> 53:23.720
right? Now we'll return to the hard questions, the interesting questions, but let me ask about

53:23.720 --> 53:34.200
human happiness. Does intelligence lead to happiness? No. So, okay, so back to the pill then.

53:34.920 --> 53:45.720
So why, when would you take the pill? So you said IQ 80, 90, 100, 110, you start going through the

53:45.800 --> 53:56.200
quartiles and is it obvious, isn't there diminishing returns and then it starts becoming negative?

53:57.240 --> 54:07.400
This is an empirical question. And so that I have advocated in many forums more research

54:08.200 --> 54:15.320
on enhancing the g-factor. Right now there's, there have been many claims about enhancing

54:15.320 --> 54:21.320
intelligence with, you mentioned the NVAC training, it was a big deal a few years ago,

54:21.320 --> 54:27.800
it doesn't work. Data is very clear, it does not work. Or doing like memory tests, like training

54:27.800 --> 54:35.160
and so on. Yeah, it may give you a better memory in the short run, but it doesn't impact your g-factor.

54:38.120 --> 54:43.880
It was very popular a couple of decades ago that the idea that listening to Mozart

54:44.520 --> 54:49.080
could make you more intelligent. There was a paper published on this with somebody I knew

54:49.080 --> 54:55.800
published this paper, intelligence researchers never believed it for a second, been hundreds of

54:55.800 --> 55:01.480
studies, all the meta-analyses, all the summaries and so on, show it, there's nothing to it,

55:02.200 --> 55:11.480
nothing to it at all. But wouldn't it be something, wouldn't it be world-shaking

55:12.680 --> 55:16.840
if you could take the normal distribution of intelligence, which we haven't really talked

55:16.840 --> 55:22.360
about yet, but IQ scores and the g-factor is thought to be a normal distribution,

55:22.680 --> 55:32.360
and shift it to the right so that everybody is smarter. Even a half a standard deviation would

55:32.360 --> 55:41.400
be world-shaking, because there are many social problems, many, many social problems that are

55:41.400 --> 55:50.280
exacerbated by people with lower ability to reason stuff out and navigate everyday life.

55:51.240 --> 55:58.520
I wonder if there's a threshold. So maybe I would push back and say universal shifting

55:59.320 --> 56:06.280
of the normal distribution may not be the optimal way of shifting. Maybe it's better to

56:07.160 --> 56:13.880
whatever the asymmetric kind of distributions is like really pushing the lower up versus

56:14.760 --> 56:20.920
trying to make the people at the average more intelligent. So you're saying that if in fact

56:20.920 --> 56:26.920
there was some way to increase g, let's just call it metaphorically a pill, an IQ pill,

56:27.640 --> 56:35.160
we should only give it to people at the lower end. No, it's just intuitively I can see that

56:35.160 --> 56:42.040
life becomes easier at the lower end if it's increased. It becomes less and less, it is

56:42.040 --> 56:48.280
a empirical scientific question, but it becomes less and less obvious to me that more intelligence

56:49.240 --> 56:57.320
is better. At the high end, not because it would make life easier, but it would make

56:57.880 --> 57:05.320
whatever problems you're working on more solvable. And if you are working on artificial

57:05.320 --> 57:13.160
intelligence, there's a tremendous potential for that to improve society.

57:13.160 --> 57:19.880
I understand. So at whatever problems you're working on, yes, but there's also the problem

57:19.880 --> 57:27.720
of the human condition. There's love, there's fear and all of those beautiful things that sometimes

57:27.720 --> 57:31.480
if you're good at solving problems, you're going to create more problems for yourself.

57:32.040 --> 57:38.280
It's, I'm not exactly sure. So ignorance is bliss is a thing. So there might be a place,

57:38.280 --> 57:43.640
there might be a sweet spot of intelligence, given your environment, given your personality,

57:43.640 --> 57:48.680
all of those kinds of things. And that becomes less beautifully complicated, the more and more

57:48.680 --> 57:54.600
intelligent you become. But that's a question for literature and not for science perhaps.

57:54.600 --> 58:00.600
Well, imagine this, imagine there was an IQ pill and it was developed by a private company.

58:01.560 --> 58:08.760
And they are willing to sell it to you. And whatever price they put on it, you are willing

58:08.760 --> 58:13.640
to pay it because you would like to be smarter. Yes. But just before they give you a pill,

58:14.200 --> 58:24.120
they give you a disclaimer form to sign. Yes. Don't hold us, you understand that this pill

58:24.120 --> 58:28.440
has no guarantee that your life is going to be better. And in fact, it could be worse.

58:29.240 --> 58:34.360
Well, yes, that's how lawyers work. But I would love for science to answer the question,

58:35.080 --> 58:37.800
to try to predict if your life is going to be better or worse,

58:38.520 --> 58:43.160
when you become more, more or less intelligent. It's a, it's a fascinating question

58:43.160 --> 58:45.560
about what is the sweet spot for the human condition.

58:47.480 --> 58:53.240
Some of the things we see as bugs might be actually features may be crucial to our

58:54.200 --> 58:59.960
overall happiness. Our limitations might lead to more happiness than less. But again,

58:59.960 --> 59:06.360
more intelligence is better at the lower end. That's more, that's something that's less arguable

59:06.360 --> 59:11.560
and, and, and, and fascinating if possible to increase. But you know, there's virtually no

59:11.560 --> 59:19.000
research that's based on a neuroscience approach to solving that problem. All the solutions that

59:19.000 --> 59:26.760
have been proposed to solve that problem or to ameliorate that problem are essentially based

59:26.760 --> 59:33.960
on the blank slate assumption that, you know, enriching the environment, removing barriers,

59:34.600 --> 59:39.560
all good things, by the way, I'm not against any of those things. But there's no empirical evidence

59:39.560 --> 59:47.160
that they're going to improve the general reasoning ability or make people more employable.

59:47.720 --> 59:50.280
Have you read Flowers of Algernon? Yes.

59:51.720 --> 59:54.280
That's to the question of intelligence and happiness.

59:56.040 --> 01:00:01.480
There are many profound aspects of that story. It was a film that was very good.

01:00:02.920 --> 01:00:07.160
The film was called Charlie for the younger people who are listening to this.

01:00:08.680 --> 01:00:14.920
You might be able to stream it on Netflix or something, but it was a story about

01:00:15.800 --> 01:00:22.440
a person with very low IQ who underwent a surgical procedure in the brain and he slowly

01:00:22.440 --> 01:00:32.680
became a genius. And the tragedy of the story is the effect was temporary. It's a fascinating story,

01:00:32.680 --> 01:00:38.280
really. That goes in contrast to the basic human experience that each of us individually have,

01:00:38.280 --> 01:00:45.240
but it raises the question of the full range of people you might be able to be,

01:00:46.680 --> 01:00:51.560
given different levels of intelligence. You've mentioned the normal distribution.

01:00:52.760 --> 01:01:00.040
So let's talk about it. There's a book called The Bell Curve written in 1994, written by psychologist

01:01:00.120 --> 01:01:06.920
Richard Hearnstein and political scientist Charles Murray. Why was this book so controversial?

01:01:08.520 --> 01:01:15.240
This is a fascinating book. I know Charles Murray. I've had many conversations with him.

01:01:15.240 --> 01:01:23.800
Yeah, what is the book about? The book is about the importance of intelligence in everyday life.

01:01:24.200 --> 01:01:32.840
That's what the book is about. It's an empirical book. It has statistical analyses of very large

01:01:32.840 --> 01:01:41.560
databases that show that essentially IQ scores or their equivalent are correlated to all kinds of

01:01:41.560 --> 01:01:51.960
social problems and social benefits. And that in itself is not where the controversy about

01:01:51.960 --> 01:01:59.240
that book came. The controversy was about one chapter in that book. And that is a chapter about

01:01:59.240 --> 01:02:05.880
the average difference in mean scores between black Americans and white Americans.

01:02:06.760 --> 01:02:11.960
And these are the terms that were used in the book at the time and are still used to some extent.

01:02:12.920 --> 01:02:26.840
And historically, or really for decades, it has been observed that disadvantaged groups

01:02:28.040 --> 01:02:38.200
score on average lower than Caucasians on academic tests, tests of mental ability,

01:02:38.200 --> 01:02:44.200
and especially on IQ tests. And the difference is about a standard deviation, which is about 15

01:02:44.200 --> 01:02:53.560
points, which is a substantial difference. In the book, Hearnstein and Murray in this one chapter

01:02:54.120 --> 01:03:04.920
assert clearly and unambiguously that whether this average difference is due to genetics or not,

01:03:05.560 --> 01:03:12.360
they are agnostic. They don't know. Moreover, they assert they don't care because you wouldn't

01:03:12.360 --> 01:03:18.440
treat anybody differently knowing that if there was a genetic component or not, because that's a

01:03:18.440 --> 01:03:25.000
group average finding. Every individual has to be treated as an individual. You can't make any

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:32.360
assumption about what that person's intellectual ability might be from the fact of an average

01:03:32.360 --> 01:03:42.200
group difference. They're very clear about this. Nonetheless, people took away, I'm going to choose

01:03:42.200 --> 01:03:48.200
my words carefully because I have a feeling that many critics didn't actually read the book,

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:53.880
they took away that Hearnstein and Murray were saying that blacks are genetically inferior.

01:03:54.840 --> 01:04:00.280
That was the take home message. And if they weren't saying it, they were implying it because they had

01:04:00.280 --> 01:04:09.560
a chapter that discussed this empirical observation of a difference. And isn't this horrible?

01:04:10.440 --> 01:04:22.680
And so the reaction to that book was incendiary. What do we know about from that book and the

01:04:22.680 --> 01:04:32.360
research beyond about race differences and intelligence? It's still the most incendiary

01:04:32.360 --> 01:04:40.280
topic in psychology. Nothing has changed that. Anybody who even discusses it is easily called

01:04:40.280 --> 01:04:47.400
a racist just for discussing it. It's become fashionable to find racism in any discussion

01:04:48.360 --> 01:04:58.840
like this. It's unfortunate. The short answer to your question is there's been very little

01:04:58.840 --> 01:05:10.440
actual research on this topic since the Belcher, even before. This really became incendiary in

01:05:10.440 --> 01:05:17.960
1969 with an article published by an educational psychologist named Arthur Jensen. Let's just

01:05:17.960 --> 01:05:24.200
take a minute and go back to that to see the bell curve in a little bit more historical perspective.

01:05:24.840 --> 01:05:34.280
Arthur Jensen was an educational psychologist at UC Berkeley. I knew him as well. And in 1969

01:05:34.280 --> 01:05:43.000
or 1968, the Harvard Educational Review asked him to do a review article on the

01:05:44.680 --> 01:05:53.320
early childhood education programs that were designed to raise the IQs of minority students.

01:05:54.680 --> 01:06:01.160
This was before the federally funded Head Start program. Head Start had not really gotten underway

01:06:01.160 --> 01:06:07.400
at the time Jensen undertook his review of what were a number of demonstration programs.

01:06:08.600 --> 01:06:15.640
And these demonstration programs were for young children around kindergarten age,

01:06:15.640 --> 01:06:22.360
and they were specially designed to be cognitively stimulating, to provide lunches,

01:06:23.080 --> 01:06:31.720
do all the things that people thought would minimize this average gap of intelligence tests.

01:06:31.720 --> 01:06:39.160
There was a strong belief among virtually all psychologists that the cause of the gap was

01:06:39.160 --> 01:06:46.440
unequal opportunity due to racism, due to all negative things in the society. And if you could

01:06:47.400 --> 01:06:54.680
compensate for this, the gap would go away. So early childhood education back then was called

01:06:54.680 --> 01:07:02.280
literally compensatory education. Jensen looked at these programs. He was an empirical guy. He

01:07:02.280 --> 01:07:12.040
understood psychometrics. And he wrote a, it was over 100 page article detailing these programs

01:07:12.120 --> 01:07:18.120
and the flaws in their research design. Some of the programs reported IQ gains of

01:07:18.120 --> 01:07:25.400
on average five points, but a few reported 10, 20, and even 30 point gains. One was called the

01:07:25.400 --> 01:07:33.560
miracle in Milwaukee. That investigator went to jail ultimately for fabricating data. But the

01:07:33.560 --> 01:07:39.400
point is that Jensen wrote an article that said, look, the opening sentence of this article is

01:07:39.400 --> 01:07:44.120
classic. The opening sentence is, I may not quote it exactly right, but it's,

01:07:44.120 --> 01:07:51.240
we have tried compensatory education and it has failed. And he showed that these games

01:07:52.680 --> 01:07:59.720
were essentially nothing. You couldn't really document empirically any gains at all from these

01:07:59.720 --> 01:08:08.120
really earnest efforts to increase IQ. But he went a step further, a fateful step further.

01:08:08.680 --> 01:08:15.880
He said, not only have these efforts failed, but because they have had essentially no impact,

01:08:15.880 --> 01:08:22.040
we have to re-examine our assumption that these differences are caused by environmental things

01:08:22.040 --> 01:08:29.160
that we can address with education. We need to consider a genetic influence, whether there's

01:08:29.160 --> 01:08:33.960
a genetic influence on this group difference. So you said that this is one of the more

01:08:33.960 --> 01:08:39.640
controversial works ever. I think it's the most infamous paper in all of psychology,

01:08:39.640 --> 01:08:48.280
I would go on to say. Because in 1969, the genetic data was very skimpy on this question.

01:08:48.280 --> 01:08:52.120
Skimpy and controversial. It's always been controversial, but it was even skimpy and

01:08:52.120 --> 01:08:59.080
controversial. It's kind of a long story that I go into a little bit in more detail in the book

01:08:59.080 --> 01:09:06.520
Neuroscience of Intelligence. But to say he was vilified is an understatement. I mean,

01:09:06.520 --> 01:09:14.040
he couldn't talk at the American Psychological Association without bomb threats clearing the

01:09:14.040 --> 01:09:21.320
lecture hall. Campus security watched him all the time. They opened his mail. He had to retreat

01:09:21.320 --> 01:09:30.440
to a different address. This was one of the earliest kinds, this is before the internet,

01:09:30.440 --> 01:09:42.040
and kind of internet social media mobs. But it was that intense. And I have written that overnight,

01:09:42.760 --> 01:09:48.920
after the publication of this article, all intelligence research became radioactive.

01:09:49.800 --> 01:09:59.640
Nobody wanted to talk about it. And then nobody was doing more research. And then

01:09:59.640 --> 01:10:06.520
the bell curve came along. And the Jensen controversy was dying down. I have stories that

01:10:06.520 --> 01:10:11.640
Jensen told me about his interaction with the Nixon White House on this issue. I mean, it was,

01:10:11.640 --> 01:10:17.800
this was like a really big deal. It was some unbelievable stories, but he told me this,

01:10:17.800 --> 01:10:25.480
so I kind of believe these stories. Nonetheless, 25 years later, 25 years later, all the silence

01:10:25.480 --> 01:10:33.720
basically saying, you know, this nobody wants to do this kind of research. There's so much pressure,

01:10:33.720 --> 01:10:42.440
so much attack against this kind of research. And here's sort of a bold, stupid, crazy people that

01:10:42.440 --> 01:10:47.640
decided to dive right back in. I wonder how much discussion that was, do we include this chapter

01:10:47.640 --> 01:10:56.200
or not? Murray has said they discussed it, and they felt they should include it. And they were

01:10:56.200 --> 01:11:05.400
very careful in the way they wrote it, which did them no good. So as a matter of fact, when the

01:11:05.400 --> 01:11:13.160
bell curve came out, it was so controversial. I got a call from a television show called Nightline,

01:11:13.160 --> 01:11:19.800
it was with a broadcaster called Ted Koppel, who had this evening show, I think it was on late at

01:11:19.800 --> 01:11:27.080
night, talked about news, it was a straight up news thing. And producer called and asked if I would

01:11:27.080 --> 01:11:34.920
be on it to talk about the bell curve. And I said, you know, she asked me what I thought

01:11:34.920 --> 01:11:39.880
about the bell curve as a book. I said, look, it's a very good book. It talks about the role of

01:11:39.880 --> 01:11:47.080
intelligence in society. And she said, no, no, what do you think about the chapter on race?

01:11:47.080 --> 01:11:53.000
That's what we want you to talk about. I remember this conversation. I said, well,

01:11:55.240 --> 01:12:02.520
she said, what would you say if you were on TV? And I said, well, what I would say is that it's

01:12:02.520 --> 01:12:09.240
not at all clear if there's any genetic component to intelligence,

01:12:11.960 --> 01:12:18.760
any differences. But if there were a strong genetic component, that would be a good thing.

01:12:21.080 --> 01:12:27.000
And, you know, complete silence on the other end of the phone. And she said, well, what do you mean?

01:12:27.960 --> 01:12:35.160
And I said, well, if it's the more genetic any difference is, the more it's biological. And

01:12:35.160 --> 01:12:41.720
if it's biological, we can figure out how to fix it. I see. That's interesting. She said,

01:12:41.720 --> 01:12:47.240
would you say that on television? Yes. I said, no. And so that was the end of that.

01:12:47.240 --> 01:13:01.240
So that's for more like biology is within the reach of science. And the environment is a public

01:13:01.240 --> 01:13:09.000
policy, social and all those kinds of things. From your perspective, whichever one you think

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:15.560
is more amenable to solutions in the short term is the one that excites you. But you're saying

01:13:15.560 --> 01:13:30.280
that it's good. The truth of genetic differences, no matter what the between groups is a painful,

01:13:31.560 --> 01:13:37.960
harmful, potentially, potentially dangerous thing. So let me ask you to this question,

01:13:37.960 --> 01:13:41.880
whether it's Bell Curve or any research on race differences,

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:50.760
can that be used to increase the amount of racism in the world? Can that be used to increase the

01:13:50.760 --> 01:13:56.200
amount of hate in the world? Do you think about this kind of stuff? I've thought about this a lot,

01:13:56.200 --> 01:14:06.840
not as a scientist, but as a person. And my sense is, there is such enormous

01:14:07.960 --> 01:14:15.560
reservoirs of hate and racism that have nothing to do with scientific knowledge of the data

01:14:16.520 --> 01:14:25.800
that speak against that. No, I don't want to give racist groups of veto power over what

01:14:25.800 --> 01:14:33.240
scientists study. If you think that the differences, and by the way, virtually no one disagrees that

01:14:33.240 --> 01:14:40.280
there are differences in scores, it's all about what causes them and how to fix it. So if you

01:14:40.280 --> 01:14:48.040
think this is a cultural problem, then you must ask the problem, do you want to change anything

01:14:48.040 --> 01:14:54.040
about the culture? Or are you okay with the culture because you don't feel it's appropriate to change

01:14:54.040 --> 01:14:59.960
a person's culture? So are you okay with that and the fact that that may lead to disadvantages in

01:14:59.960 --> 01:15:07.400
school achievement? It's a question. If you think it's environmental, what are the environmental

01:15:07.960 --> 01:15:15.880
parameters that can be fixed? I'll tell you one, lead from gasoline in the atmosphere,

01:15:15.880 --> 01:15:23.080
lead in paint, lead in water. That's an environmental toxin that society has the means to

01:15:23.720 --> 01:15:28.200
eliminate, and they should. Yeah, just to sort of try and define some

01:15:29.640 --> 01:15:37.640
insight and conclusion to this very difficult topic. Is there been research on environment

01:15:37.640 --> 01:15:41.240
versus genetics, nature versus nurture on this question of race differences?

01:15:44.280 --> 01:15:49.480
No one wants to do this research. First of all, it's hard research to do. Second of all, it's a

01:15:49.480 --> 01:15:54.520
minefield. No one wants to spend their career on it. Tenured people don't want to do it,

01:15:54.520 --> 01:16:02.360
let alone students. The way I talk about it, well, before I tell you the way I talk about it,

01:16:02.360 --> 01:16:08.040
I want to say one more thing about Jensen. He was once asked by a journalist straight out,

01:16:08.040 --> 01:16:15.400
are you a racist? His answer was very interesting. His answer was, I've thought about that a lot,

01:16:15.720 --> 01:16:23.640
and I've concluded it doesn't matter. Now, I know what he meant by this.

01:16:23.640 --> 01:16:25.800
The guts to say that. Wow.

01:16:25.800 --> 01:16:30.440
He was a very unusual person. I think he had a touch of Asperger's syndrome to tell you the

01:16:30.440 --> 01:16:36.040
truth, because I saw him in many circumstances. He would be canceled on Twitter immediately

01:16:36.040 --> 01:16:40.680
with that sentence. Yeah, but what he meant was he had a hypothesis,

01:16:41.640 --> 01:16:47.800
yeah, and with respect to group differences, he called it the default hypothesis. He said,

01:16:47.800 --> 01:16:53.400
whatever factors affect individual intelligence are likely the same factors that affect group

01:16:53.400 --> 01:17:00.200
differences. It was the default, but it was a hypothesis. It should be tested, and if it turned

01:17:00.200 --> 01:17:05.560
out, empirical test didn't support the hypothesis, he was happy to move on to something else.

01:17:06.360 --> 01:17:15.160
He was absolutely committed to that scientific ideal, that it's an empirical question.

01:17:15.960 --> 01:17:18.680
We should look at it, and let's see what happens.

01:17:18.680 --> 01:17:24.520
The scientific method cannot be racist from his perspective. It doesn't matter what the

01:17:24.520 --> 01:17:31.960
scientists, if they follow the scientific method, it doesn't matter what they believe.

01:17:31.960 --> 01:17:38.600
And if they are biased, and they consciously or unconsciously bias the data,

01:17:39.400 --> 01:17:47.480
other people will come along to replicate it, they will fail, and the process over time will work.

01:17:48.120 --> 01:17:55.960
So let me push back on this idea, because psychology to me is full of gray areas,

