02:15:11.080 --> 02:15:17.400
at this. These were really the first studies of brain imaging using positron emission tomography

02:15:18.360 --> 02:15:27.160
long before fMRI. And you would inject a radioactive sugar that labeled the brain,

02:15:27.160 --> 02:15:31.640
and the harder the brain was working, the more sugar it would take up. And then you could make

02:15:31.640 --> 02:15:40.840
a picture of glucose use in the brain. And he was amazing. He managed to do this in normal

02:15:40.840 --> 02:15:49.640
volunteers he brought in and anesthetized as if they were going into surgery. He managed all

02:15:49.640 --> 02:15:59.800
the human subjects requirements on this research. And he was brilliant at this. And what we did

02:15:59.800 --> 02:16:06.520
is we had these normal volunteers come in on three occasions. On one occasion, he gave them

02:16:06.520 --> 02:16:16.760
enough anesthetic drug so they were a little drowsy. And on another occasion, they came in

02:16:16.760 --> 02:16:27.000
and he fully anesthetized them. And he would say, Mike, can you hear me? And the person would say,

02:16:27.000 --> 02:16:38.600
oh, yeah. And then we would scan people under no anesthetic condition. So the same person.

02:16:39.400 --> 02:16:47.320
And we were looking to see if we could see the part of the brain turn off. He subsequently

02:16:47.320 --> 02:16:53.240
tried to do this with fMRI, which has a faster time resolution. And you could do it in real time

02:16:53.240 --> 02:16:57.640
as the person went under and then regained consciousness where you couldn't do that with

02:16:57.640 --> 02:17:03.240
PET. You had to have three different occasions. And the results were absolutely fascinating.

02:17:03.240 --> 02:17:08.760
We did this with different anesthetic drugs. And different drugs impacted different parts of the

02:17:08.760 --> 02:17:15.960
brain. So we were naturally looking for the common one. And it seemed to have something to do with

02:17:15.960 --> 02:17:24.760
